95
00:05:05,307 --> 00:05:09,209
So I joined the team in February of 2015.

96
00:05:10,310 --> 00:05:12,691
So the very first thing I did was a big analysis

97
00:05:13,091 --> 00:05:14,292
of all that preexisting art,

98
00:05:14,312 --> 00:05:16,394
and I tried to articulate in objective terms

99
00:05:18,055 --> 00:05:19,496
why I thought it was coming up short.

100
00:05:19,856 --> 00:05:20,576
Here's some of that stuff.

101
00:05:21,943 --> 00:05:22,643
Art fundamentals.

102
00:05:22,843 --> 00:05:25,184
So basically the stuff that you would learn in art class.

103
00:05:25,885 --> 00:05:27,686
They weren't being used to communicate

104
00:05:27,786 --> 00:05:29,567
important information to the player.

105
00:05:30,867 --> 00:05:34,209
So value, the artists in the room know what that is.

106
00:05:34,469 --> 00:05:37,271
It's how light and dark something is, basically.

107
00:05:38,712 --> 00:05:40,392
It's great for making things stand out.

108
00:05:40,533 --> 00:05:42,814
So what's the important stuff in an RTS?

109
00:05:42,874 --> 00:05:45,935
Well, that's going to be your units, or your buildings,

110
00:05:46,155 --> 00:05:48,176
or in the case of tooth and tail, your commander.

111
00:05:48,917 --> 00:05:52,038
You want those things to be higher contrast, so darker

112
00:05:52,078 --> 00:05:54,039
darks and brighter brights all in the same area.

113
00:05:54,599 --> 00:05:56,360
And you want the less critical stuff.

114
00:05:56,940 --> 00:06:00,342
random terrain and whatever you want that to be a little bit more right in

115
00:06:00,362 --> 00:06:05,083
the middle. Little bit more even if we if we look at one of these old images

116
00:06:05,143 --> 00:06:08,245
in grayscale we can kind of see that that that rat commander right in the

117
00:06:08,265 --> 00:06:10,706
middle kind of those grays are kind of following.

118
00:06:12,006 --> 00:06:15,489
falling right along the same level of gray as the rest of the image.

119
00:06:15,529 --> 00:06:17,952
That rat's not really popping out because of value.

120
00:06:18,592 --> 00:06:21,936
In the terrain itself, there's these kind of like undulating darks and lights, but there's

121
00:06:21,996 --> 00:06:23,257
no real rhyme or reason to it.

122
00:06:23,597 --> 00:06:27,881
The one effective bit going on is those pigs, which are an important part of the game, those

123
00:06:27,921 --> 00:06:30,304
are really popping off that dark terrain.

124
00:06:30,624 --> 00:06:33,527
But overall, this is just not a very effective use of value.

125
00:06:34,716 --> 00:06:36,957
color wasn't really being used effectively either.

126
00:06:37,057 --> 00:06:39,857
So we have one smart bit going on.

127
00:06:39,877 --> 00:06:42,698
We've got this kind of orange, red rat

128
00:06:42,758 --> 00:06:44,458
on top of mostly green terrain,

129
00:06:44,478 --> 00:06:46,259
and that's a pretty classic example

130
00:06:46,359 --> 00:06:48,219
of complementary colors,

131
00:06:49,379 --> 00:06:51,920
which is similar to how there's a joke

132
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,340
about how all movie posters are blue and orange.

133
00:06:56,401 --> 00:06:58,382
Kind of funny to see all of these spread out.

134
00:06:58,422 --> 00:06:59,422
They all kind of look the same,

135
00:06:59,462 --> 00:07:00,502
but the fact of the matter is,

136
00:07:00,542 --> 00:07:02,963
is complementary colors can be pretty striking

137
00:07:03,003 --> 00:07:04,563
when used skillfully.

138
00:07:05,123 --> 00:07:06,224
But in the case of Tooth and Tail,

139
00:07:06,244 --> 00:07:08,324
it wasn't really pushed far enough and it wasn't consistent.

140
00:07:08,885 --> 00:07:11,985
For instance, if I played as any other commander,

141
00:07:12,886 --> 00:07:13,986
my faction color would change

142
00:07:14,026 --> 00:07:16,567
and I would lose that complementary color relationship.

143
00:07:18,587 --> 00:07:20,749
Additionally, speaking of faction color,

144
00:07:21,750 --> 00:07:23,771
if we look at the faction color of the units,

145
00:07:24,132 --> 00:07:26,434
it's red, but those reds are really dark

146
00:07:26,474 --> 00:07:28,435
and kind of under saturated.

147
00:07:28,475 --> 00:07:30,517
The saturation is lower than the terrain,

148
00:07:30,537 --> 00:07:32,318
so they don't really pop off the terrain.

149
00:07:33,179 --> 00:07:34,920
Overall, the color palette kind of felt

150
00:07:35,261 --> 00:07:36,882
a little subdued and sleepy,

151
00:07:37,222 --> 00:07:38,984
and definitely didn't prime the player

152
00:07:39,024 --> 00:07:42,086
for the kind of like fast, quick action

153
00:07:42,547 --> 00:07:44,268
that the game is kind of made of.

154
00:07:45,609 --> 00:07:49,933
Related to those art fundamentals, character designs were overly complex.

155
00:07:49,953 --> 00:07:57,321
Now, I'm a big believer that all design, character design, game design, industrial design, graphic design, all of it,

156
00:07:57,681 --> 00:07:59,983
it's not really about what you can add but what you can take away.

157
00:08:01,592 --> 00:08:06,176
The units in Tooth and Tail when I joined the team were like detailed little paintings

158
00:08:06,416 --> 00:08:10,079
which made them really, really cool paintings, but kind of poor character designs.

159
00:08:10,799 --> 00:08:14,782
When you got a bunch of them in a mob, which is a pretty common occurrence in the game,

160
00:08:16,043 --> 00:08:19,626
all that detail kind of just became this undulating block of noise.

161
00:08:19,666 --> 00:08:22,328
It made it really hard to see what was actually going on.

162
00:08:23,228 --> 00:08:25,550
One of the biggest issues here was that silhouette.

163
00:08:26,550 --> 00:08:29,534
wasn't consciously considered when designing the units.

164
00:08:29,594 --> 00:08:31,456
All the units had kind of a similar posture,

165
00:08:32,256 --> 00:08:33,858
similar volume, a lot of them carried

166
00:08:33,938 --> 00:08:35,820
kind of similarly sized weapons.

167
00:08:36,220 --> 00:08:40,245
Now, this maybe seems insignificant or even silly,

168
00:08:40,305 --> 00:08:42,767
talking about silhouette, but it's actually

169
00:08:43,328 --> 00:08:45,350
one of the most powerful tools in a character designer's.

170
00:08:46,391 --> 00:08:49,514
Toolkit, it helps maybe more than anything, that five second read.

171
00:08:50,695 --> 00:08:51,776
Something to kind of think about.

172
00:08:51,916 --> 00:08:57,301
It's not an accident that there are no background characters in The Simpsons that have the same

173
00:08:57,361 --> 00:08:59,863
like head shape as Lisa or Bart or Marge.

174
00:09:00,684 --> 00:09:03,826
If you want something to stand out in a crowd, give it a unique silhouette.

175
00:09:04,227 --> 00:09:07,910
And even better, put some useful information into that silhouette.

176
00:09:09,832 --> 00:09:12,012
Another problem, the visual design of the environment

177
00:09:12,052 --> 00:09:15,493
was straddling between organic and board game-like

178
00:09:15,533 --> 00:09:17,033
in a way that undermined the narrative.

179
00:09:17,554 --> 00:09:18,614
What is the narrative?

180
00:09:19,514 --> 00:09:21,115
In the world of Tooth and Tail,

181
00:09:21,675 --> 00:09:24,856
an unspecified calamity wipes out all the crops,

182
00:09:25,276 --> 00:09:26,736
causes a massive food shortage,

183
00:09:27,216 --> 00:09:29,957
and all animals, even herbivores,

184
00:09:29,997 --> 00:09:31,577
they're forced to eat meat to survive.

185
00:09:32,558 --> 00:09:35,178
But then they all kind of decide they like to eat meat.

186
00:09:35,338 --> 00:09:35,978
They prefer it.

187
00:09:37,059 --> 00:09:37,659
So this...

188
00:09:39,160 --> 00:09:44,145
War is ultimately about who gets to be the people and who has to be the meat.

189
00:09:45,446 --> 00:09:50,731
It's modeled loosely around conflicts, the dawn of mechanized warfare, so World War I,

190
00:09:50,751 --> 00:09:53,214
but I think more specifically the Russian Revolution.

191
00:09:53,694 --> 00:09:55,736
So this is not a happy place.

192
00:09:57,372 --> 00:09:59,453
But the tile approach that was being used

193
00:09:59,493 --> 00:10:01,694
when I joined the project kind of undermined all that.

194
00:10:01,714 --> 00:10:04,616
We're saying it's about terrible social upheaval

195
00:10:04,696 --> 00:10:07,017
and this kind of unprecedented carnage

196
00:10:07,077 --> 00:10:09,018
and a genie that's been let out of the bottle,

197
00:10:09,098 --> 00:10:12,660
but what we're showing you is like

198
00:10:12,760 --> 00:10:15,381
Marble Madness special edition re-release.

199
00:10:17,323 --> 00:10:18,743
If you're too young to know what that is,

200
00:10:18,803 --> 00:10:20,804
that's a game that like cavemen played

201
00:10:21,725 --> 00:10:23,046
going to dinosaur school.

202
00:10:25,854 --> 00:10:28,217
just look it up it looks just like that uh...

203
00:10:28,558 --> 00:10:31,862
okay so another problem there is no uh... achievable and goal defined

204
00:10:32,143 --> 00:10:34,446
basically there is no like actionable mock-up

205
00:10:35,894 --> 00:10:38,876
The mockups that were made looked super nice,

206
00:10:38,956 --> 00:10:42,379
but these were really paintings and not proper mockups.

207
00:10:42,719 --> 00:10:44,461
Given the tech that the game was built on,

208
00:10:44,501 --> 00:10:47,303
there's really no way of recreating this in game,

209
00:10:47,363 --> 00:10:50,125
so you're still left with this big open question

210
00:10:50,445 --> 00:10:52,867
of like, okay, well, this is great,

211
00:10:52,907 --> 00:10:55,369
but what does the game actually look like?

212
00:10:55,569 --> 00:10:59,051
The arc lacked a solid direction to head in.

213
00:11:01,313 --> 00:11:05,358
Another problem was that there were a few thoroughly tested ARP pipelines in place.

214
00:11:05,398 --> 00:11:10,804
Now, PocketWatch likes rolling their own engine, and the engine had all the support for like

215
00:11:10,844 --> 00:11:12,465
the major features you would expect.

216
00:11:12,505 --> 00:11:16,310
It had actors, and it had objects, and it had a bunch of environmental stuff, and it

217
00:11:16,390 --> 00:11:18,052
had particle effects, and all this kind of stuff.

218
00:11:19,473 --> 00:11:26,143
But nothing was really documented and an experienced artist never really put all of that stuff

219
00:11:26,403 --> 00:11:27,184
through its paces.

220
00:11:27,285 --> 00:11:31,170
So there were big questions about where the weak points in the tech were.

221
00:11:33,395 --> 00:11:35,175
And then finally, the last little bit of critique,

222
00:11:35,195 --> 00:11:36,156
there was no art director.

223
00:11:36,216 --> 00:11:40,477
So IndieShots, again, the main pocket watch guy,

224
00:11:41,818 --> 00:11:44,319
he was playing art director while he was also

225
00:11:44,379 --> 00:11:46,579
being a designer and running a business

226
00:11:46,819 --> 00:11:49,800
and being a programmer, and even in the indie space,

227
00:11:50,241 --> 00:11:52,801
which is kind of known for people wearing multiple hats,

228
00:11:52,882 --> 00:11:54,202
I think that was one hat too many.

229
00:11:56,023 --> 00:11:57,763
I think another thing, though, was

230
00:12:00,151 --> 00:12:02,591
Andy does have some experience as an artist.

231
00:12:02,692 --> 00:12:04,292
He actually has an art degree,

232
00:12:04,572 --> 00:12:06,952
and he paints and a bunch of stuff.

233
00:12:06,972 --> 00:12:08,153
He's actually a pretty decent painter.

234
00:12:08,973 --> 00:12:12,694
But he hasn't spent years solving visual problems.

235
00:12:13,274 --> 00:12:17,075
And if you've got a stack of visual problems to solve,

236
00:12:17,235 --> 00:12:19,375
it's gonna be most efficient to have someone

237
00:12:19,455 --> 00:12:20,955
who does have experience doing that,

238
00:12:21,336 --> 00:12:22,536
trying to work through that stack.

239
00:12:23,776 --> 00:12:27,679
Another thing I did was I took stock of the things Pocket Watch had going for them.

240
00:12:28,940 --> 00:12:31,861
And the top of that list was the painter in the project, Jerome Jacinto.

241
00:12:32,722 --> 00:12:37,965
Jerome is awesome. All the art that I just spent 10 minutes critiquing was made by Jerome.

242
00:12:38,005 --> 00:12:43,929
But Jerome is an incredible painter. He can paint circles around me all day before I even get out of bed.

243
00:12:44,889 --> 00:12:46,290
And he's just awesome to work with.

244
00:12:47,211 --> 00:12:51,353
But at the time I came on board, I think he was still pretty green in terms of being a game artist.

245
00:12:52,798 --> 00:12:55,061
he knew how to make a still image that would blow you away

246
00:12:55,442 --> 00:12:59,046
but uh... hadn't yet developed a ton of experience kind of wrestling with the

247
00:12:59,106 --> 00:12:59,747
complex

248
00:13:00,568 --> 00:13:03,573
uh... changing informational landscape that is a game

249
00:13:03,813 --> 00:13:07,378
but it was pretty clear that with uh... just even a little bit of direction he

250
00:13:07,398 --> 00:13:10,061
was going to be like a super weapon and that that was the case

251
00:13:11,681 --> 00:13:14,344
So lessons, I'm gonna be calling out key lessons

252
00:13:14,544 --> 00:13:17,066
at regular intervals and I'm hoping,

253
00:13:18,047 --> 00:13:22,011
my aim is that these lessons are broader

254
00:13:22,071 --> 00:13:23,153
than the talk itself.

255
00:13:23,573 --> 00:13:26,136
They're things that you can apply to all kinds of art making

256
00:13:26,176 --> 00:13:27,497
not just like 2D stuff,

257
00:13:27,917 --> 00:13:29,399
but even hopefully other disciplines.

258
00:13:29,439 --> 00:13:30,280
So here's the first batch.

259
00:13:33,260 --> 00:13:36,401
Even if you are crunched for time,

260
00:13:36,901 --> 00:13:38,762
allowing yourself to stop and think

261
00:13:38,922 --> 00:13:40,443
kind of about what you're doing

262
00:13:41,023 --> 00:13:43,264
usually ends up paying dividends

263
00:13:43,464 --> 00:13:45,846
in the form of, in productivity.

264
00:13:46,126 --> 00:13:47,866
You end up working faster

265
00:13:47,986 --> 00:13:49,207
after you have that time to think

266
00:13:49,247 --> 00:13:50,848
and you end up making less mistakes.

267
00:13:51,548 --> 00:13:54,129
I know it's super stressful, potentially,

268
00:13:54,389 --> 00:13:57,391
because stopping to think does not feel

269
00:13:57,611 --> 00:13:58,611
as much like work.

270
00:13:59,292 --> 00:14:02,914
as like trying to just like brute force your way through an asset list.

271
00:14:03,754 --> 00:14:06,176
But in my experience, it has always been worth it.

272
00:14:09,298 --> 00:14:11,579
Another one. Fancy tools are awesome.

273
00:14:11,879 --> 00:14:16,662
And we have tons and tons of fancy tools in 2017.

274
00:14:16,702 --> 00:14:16,762
But...

275
00:14:20,399 --> 00:14:26,188
I won't say they're useless, but they're not as useful as they could be if you don't understand

276
00:14:26,248 --> 00:14:29,012
visual design basics.

277
00:14:29,232 --> 00:14:33,178
If you want to develop these skills, skip the...

278
00:14:35,381 --> 00:14:38,203
how to model a soldier in Blender tutorial

279
00:14:38,944 --> 00:14:41,206
and go for like basic color theory

280
00:14:41,546 --> 00:14:44,289
or understanding anatomy or something like that.

281
00:14:44,329 --> 00:14:45,670
And even if you aren't an artist,

282
00:14:46,350 --> 00:14:47,471
checking out something like that,

283
00:14:47,552 --> 00:14:49,033
you're gonna be able to talk to artists

284
00:14:49,193 --> 00:14:50,154
way more effectively.

285
00:14:50,934 --> 00:14:53,497
And maybe prototyping even goes better.

286
00:14:53,537 --> 00:14:55,118
So I think it's a good exercise.

287
00:14:56,232 --> 00:15:00,516
And then three, it may seem like semantics at first blush,

288
00:15:00,576 --> 00:15:03,859
but I think there is a really important distinction

289
00:15:03,899 --> 00:15:07,602
between being a game artist and being an animator

290
00:15:07,782 --> 00:15:08,763
or a 3D modeler.

291
00:15:09,323 --> 00:15:11,845
The artwork in games is, I think,

292
00:15:13,077 --> 00:15:17,399
in its purest form, visual communication of the gameplay.

293
00:15:17,919 --> 00:15:20,540
Yes, it's also there to kind of get people amped

294
00:15:21,101 --> 00:15:23,322
and keep people there once they're there,

295
00:15:24,362 --> 00:15:27,084
but you can kind of take those things away.

296
00:15:27,104 --> 00:15:30,686
And the art still works as long

297
00:15:30,706 --> 00:15:32,807
as it's communicating the design.

298
00:15:34,292 --> 00:15:37,435
There's another discipline that is primarily concerned

299
00:15:37,535 --> 00:15:39,617
with visual communication of information,

300
00:15:39,677 --> 00:15:41,058
and that's just graphic design.

301
00:15:41,138 --> 00:15:43,761
So besides those art fundamentals

302
00:15:43,781 --> 00:15:44,842
that I was just talking about,

303
00:15:45,202 --> 00:15:47,544
you know, learn about branding and typography.

304
00:15:47,845 --> 00:15:49,746
Like, dive down into this kind of stuff.

305
00:15:49,807 --> 00:15:50,647
Do research about.

306
00:15:51,608 --> 00:15:54,471
subway maps or signs in like tourist areas

307
00:15:54,871 --> 00:15:56,933
and then try and draw the connections between

308
00:15:57,614 --> 00:15:59,255
what makes that stuff successful

309
00:15:59,855 --> 00:16:02,238
and what makes an interesting character design

310
00:16:02,278 --> 00:16:05,000
or an interesting, the design of a locale

311
00:16:05,040 --> 00:16:05,821
or something like that.

312
00:16:07,577 --> 00:16:10,758
Okay, so we knew what the problems were,

313
00:16:10,778 --> 00:16:13,840
and now it was time to start addressing them.

314
00:16:13,940 --> 00:16:16,121
The very first thing I did was I made a new mock-up

315
00:16:16,581 --> 00:16:19,322
that addressed those formal issues I just talked about

316
00:16:19,362 --> 00:16:22,604
while also trying to reinforce the game's narrative.

317
00:16:23,404 --> 00:16:28,872
I kept it super simple at the beginning because I wanted to be sure we could easily talk about

318
00:16:28,972 --> 00:16:30,254
everything that was there.

319
00:16:30,274 --> 00:16:33,559
I wanted all of these early ideas to be properly critiqued.

320
00:16:33,579 --> 00:16:35,923
I wanted nothing to be lost in the mix.

321
00:16:36,023 --> 00:16:37,525
And I wanted everyone to understand like...

322
00:16:38,486 --> 00:16:39,386
uh... why

323
00:16:39,807 --> 00:16:42,248
we wanted to do each one of these things basically

324
00:16:42,268 --> 00:16:45,309
uh... metaphor that we can kind of think of

325
00:16:45,789 --> 00:16:48,650
i'm trying to like lay a really solid foundation here

326
00:16:49,451 --> 00:16:53,912
uh... and maybe like sketch out a floor plan but in no way am i

327
00:16:53,953 --> 00:16:55,353
trying to show a finished house

328
00:16:56,714 --> 00:16:57,796
I think there's a lesson in that.

329
00:16:57,936 --> 00:16:59,738
Baby steps, I'm gonna come back to baby steps

330
00:16:59,878 --> 00:17:01,761
again and again throughout this career.

331
00:17:01,901 --> 00:17:04,725
It ensures an entire team, especially a remote team.

332
00:17:05,065 --> 00:17:07,909
I was remote, Pocket Watch Games is in San Diego,

333
00:17:08,009 --> 00:17:08,610
I live in Maine.

334
00:17:10,631 --> 00:17:14,173
It ensures that an entire team can kind of keep up

335
00:17:14,193 --> 00:17:16,594
and it stops problems, like small problems,

336
00:17:16,694 --> 00:17:17,935
from becoming compounded.

337
00:17:19,495 --> 00:17:22,177
I think also if you ensure an entire team

338
00:17:22,237 --> 00:17:24,818
is moving together, you're kind of sharing the experience

339
00:17:25,298 --> 00:17:27,439
of making that game and I think you're more likely

340
00:17:27,499 --> 00:17:30,481
to be on the same wavelength in terms of communication.

341
00:17:32,397 --> 00:17:34,957
So this mockup was made with actionability in mind.

342
00:17:34,997 --> 00:17:37,578
It only included artwork or features

343
00:17:37,658 --> 00:17:38,999
that I knew we could add.

344
00:17:39,599 --> 00:17:42,020
There wasn't any bit of art here that made me say like,

345
00:17:42,100 --> 00:17:42,980
oh, well this is cool,

346
00:17:43,020 --> 00:17:44,801
but I don't know how we're gonna do this yet.

347
00:17:46,321 --> 00:17:47,882
No new questions, only answers.

348
00:17:49,222 --> 00:17:51,323
Let's go through some of these things bit by bit.

349
00:17:52,163 --> 00:17:55,066
So one suggestion was instead of those like grid blocks,

350
00:17:55,166 --> 00:18:00,210
then the checkerboard that the game was using before,

351
00:18:01,431 --> 00:18:04,374
I suggested we do a fill of like much larger textures

352
00:18:04,454 --> 00:18:05,915
at the base level of the world,

353
00:18:05,975 --> 00:18:07,376
kind of underneath the cliffs

354
00:18:07,436 --> 00:18:08,657
and underneath the units and stuff.

355
00:18:08,718 --> 00:18:10,539
And that was to help reduce patterning,

356
00:18:10,879 --> 00:18:12,541
make the world feel a little bit more organic

357
00:18:12,621 --> 00:18:13,922
and get rid of that checkerboard effect.

358
00:18:15,942 --> 00:18:21,324
I suggested we use a shader, even just like an old-fashioned overlay image, to shift the

359
00:18:21,364 --> 00:18:25,426
color of the terrain so as to get a little bit more color variation, make it feel a little

360
00:18:25,446 --> 00:18:26,186
bit more organic.

361
00:18:29,387 --> 00:18:34,950
And I suggested some simple atmospheric overlays, so cloud shadows that scroll across the ground

362
00:18:35,030 --> 00:18:38,011
and animated sun rays on a post-process tint.

363
00:18:38,051 --> 00:18:42,573
This was to help push the value range and make the whole scene feel a little bit more

364
00:18:42,593 --> 00:18:43,013
dramatic.

365
00:18:47,298 --> 00:18:53,001
There's also some changes here meant to solve some like mundane but critical

366
00:18:53,041 --> 00:18:57,963
problems. So an example Z fighting or like bad sorting was a problem with the

367
00:18:57,983 --> 00:19:03,546
way the the old terrain work sometimes units would render behind squares that

368
00:19:03,566 --> 00:19:09,089
they were in front of and vice versa. So I suggested we paint terrain are we

369
00:19:09,429 --> 00:19:13,431
rather pink cliffs and ramps in such a way that you can never actually get

370
00:19:13,571 --> 00:19:14,151
behind them.

371
00:19:15,832 --> 00:19:18,598
A lesson for junior artists, or really actually all artists,

372
00:19:18,959 --> 00:19:22,286
that if you can reduce like bugs for coders,

373
00:19:22,346 --> 00:19:24,330
they will love you forever, and do that.

374
00:19:25,152 --> 00:19:25,553
Just do that.

375
00:19:27,180 --> 00:19:29,403
So the mock-up was well-received,

376
00:19:29,643 --> 00:19:31,405
and I don't want to put words into anybody's mouth,

377
00:19:31,425 --> 00:19:33,908
but I think everyone kind of felt reinvigorated a little bit.

378
00:19:35,189 --> 00:19:37,472
And it was around this time that Andy said,

379
00:19:38,113 --> 00:19:38,913
like paraphrased,

380
00:19:41,116 --> 00:19:42,818
I always imagine this as a pixel art game.

381
00:19:42,858 --> 00:19:43,799
Can we do pixel art?

382
00:19:43,859 --> 00:19:45,180
Is that even a good idea?

383
00:19:45,200 --> 00:19:45,881
Would that work?

384
00:19:46,342 --> 00:19:47,443
How does that change the schedule?

385
00:19:47,763 --> 00:19:48,244
Can we do it?

386
00:19:50,832 --> 00:19:57,019
I loved that suggestion because Command and Conquer 1, the very first one, was the game

387
00:19:57,079 --> 00:20:02,025
I was obsessively playing when I realized it was like someone's job to make games and

388
00:20:02,065 --> 00:20:04,248
like holy shit I could be one of those guys.

389
00:20:06,097 --> 00:20:10,201
to make a strategy game with big chunky pixels was like a pilgrimage for me.

390
00:20:11,682 --> 00:20:14,445
But more important than that personal excitement

391
00:20:15,566 --> 00:20:20,290
was the fact that moving tooth and tail to a pixel style kind of spoke to the game's soul better.

392
00:20:20,951 --> 00:20:24,554
After all, it's a bit of a love letter to those classic 90s strategy games,

393
00:20:24,574 --> 00:20:29,278
while also being a little bit of a love letter to some classic arcade games and like arcade culture.

394
00:20:30,715 --> 00:20:33,636
It also simplified animation production tremendously.

395
00:20:33,956 --> 00:20:36,097
Before, it was a bit of an open question

396
00:20:36,117 --> 00:20:37,457
of how we would actually produce

397
00:20:37,557 --> 00:20:38,818
all of the animation in the game.

398
00:20:39,698 --> 00:20:42,679
It would probably require a new tech or be expensive.

399
00:20:43,179 --> 00:20:45,300
Would we use like a 2D rig system?

400
00:20:45,360 --> 00:20:49,001
Would we model and animate everything in 3D?

401
00:20:49,081 --> 00:20:53,023
Would we do like high-res hand-painted animation?

402
00:20:53,983 --> 00:20:54,143
Nope.

403
00:20:54,883 --> 00:20:57,363
we would use good old-fashioned hand-drawn pixely sprites.

404
00:20:58,384 --> 00:21:01,064
We could focus entirely on broad gesture

405
00:21:01,124 --> 00:21:03,285
without getting caught in expensive details.

406
00:21:04,925 --> 00:21:07,986
Relatively nice and easy compared to those other options,

407
00:21:08,006 --> 00:21:10,266
and it works with our existing tech, great.

408
00:21:11,546 --> 00:21:13,427
So the first pixel mock-up was a hit,

409
00:21:13,867 --> 00:21:16,487
and again, while it was a little bit thin at the start,

410
00:21:16,627 --> 00:21:20,368
it proved to be the perfect foundation on which to build,

411
00:21:20,428 --> 00:21:22,569
but I will get to that in just a second,

412
00:21:22,989 --> 00:21:24,269
because let's do some lessons first.

413
00:21:26,636 --> 00:21:34,583
If you pick an art style that plays to your team's strengths and speaks to your core experience,

414
00:21:34,603 --> 00:21:37,825
you reduce the number of visual problems that you actually have to solve.

415
00:21:39,527 --> 00:21:44,731
It makes you and your team saner because you're not trying to figure out a way to say X.

416
00:21:47,308 --> 00:21:51,373
with the visual language that just isn't well-equipped to say x

417
00:21:53,075 --> 00:21:55,999
in our case pixels spoke to the soul of the game

418
00:21:56,019 --> 00:21:59,403
uh... really nicely it it's all the bunch of technical problems

419
00:21:59,804 --> 00:22:02,107
and it was faster produce so is a plus for us

420
00:22:03,989 --> 00:22:08,772
And two, a mock-up is a tool, and I think in some cases,

421
00:22:09,853 --> 00:22:11,714
in my experience, maybe even most cases,

422
00:22:12,454 --> 00:22:14,555
it's the most valuable tool you have.

423
00:22:14,935 --> 00:22:17,277
It's not just a painting or a fancy render.

424
00:22:18,197 --> 00:22:20,739
It can often give you a leg up on production too,

425
00:22:21,139 --> 00:22:23,060
because the assets you make in the mock-up

426
00:22:23,100 --> 00:22:24,581
can just be moved into a build.

427
00:22:24,921 --> 00:22:26,402
So in my experience, it's always been good

428
00:22:26,442 --> 00:22:30,184
to spend real time on it and not think of it as like,

429
00:22:30,204 --> 00:22:31,465
oh, we just have to get this done

430
00:22:31,485 --> 00:22:32,886
and then we can start making the real art.

431
00:22:35,252 --> 00:22:36,113
Okay, let's keep going.

432
00:22:36,293 --> 00:22:39,335
So we had a mock-up, we had total team buy-in,

433
00:22:39,896 --> 00:22:42,418
we were all excited about pixels, there we go.

434
00:22:43,899 --> 00:22:45,580
At this point, we started pushing forward

435
00:22:45,600 --> 00:22:46,401
on multiple fronts.

436
00:22:46,581 --> 00:22:48,362
So Jerome and I dove into character design,

437
00:22:48,402 --> 00:22:52,125
we did just iteration after iteration of line art.

438
00:22:52,545 --> 00:22:55,787
This is like the tiniest tip of the iceberg,

439
00:22:55,848 --> 00:22:59,610
I would need all of the walls to show everything we did,

440
00:22:59,630 --> 00:23:00,491
it was exhaustive.

441
00:23:02,352 --> 00:23:08,461
Jerome himself did a bunch of like paintings exploring a bunch of different fun, none of these are fun,

442
00:23:09,062 --> 00:23:12,527
but different, but fun potential scenarios and emotional themes.

443
00:23:12,587 --> 00:23:15,791
I want to make a game just about this dog getting his hat shot.

444
00:23:16,753 --> 00:23:19,256
That doesn't show up in the game, but it should probably.

445
00:23:21,321 --> 00:23:27,325
So the end result of all this work was a nice set of guidelines that dictated the visual design of our units.

446
00:23:27,385 --> 00:23:30,307
So units in a given tier, we've got these three tiers.

447
00:23:30,407 --> 00:23:38,092
Units in a given tier all stand in different poses or have drastically different equipment or weapons

448
00:23:38,172 --> 00:23:40,914
so as to help the silhouette be as informative as possible.

449
00:23:41,734 --> 00:23:46,597
Reptiles are primitive. They have less clothing and they generally have melee attacks.

450
00:23:47,758 --> 00:23:50,860
Mammals wear more clothing and are generally ranged.

451
00:23:52,381 --> 00:23:54,983
Scale clearly denotes combat effectiveness.

452
00:23:55,904 --> 00:23:56,984
One thing that I've learned

453
00:23:59,586 --> 00:24:01,688
is that my job as a visual designer,

454
00:24:02,528 --> 00:24:05,210
it's not just to design stuff that looks cool,

455
00:24:05,410 --> 00:24:07,071
it's to design stuff that allows

456
00:24:07,111 --> 00:24:08,552
for a suspension of disbelief.

457
00:24:09,393 --> 00:24:12,295
And creating a consistent visual language,

458
00:24:13,095 --> 00:24:16,718
something that has order and patterns and stuff,

459
00:24:17,318 --> 00:24:18,359
really helps do that.

460
00:24:20,578 --> 00:24:23,079
The mockup itself became something of a living document.

461
00:24:23,159 --> 00:24:26,401
So if anyone had any idea for art,

462
00:24:27,281 --> 00:24:29,442
it was iterated a half dozen times in the mockup

463
00:24:29,482 --> 00:24:31,943
before we ever actually put anything in the build.

464
00:24:32,543 --> 00:24:34,544
One of the best pieces of advice I ever got

465
00:24:34,584 --> 00:24:35,924
from my first art director was,

466
00:24:36,565 --> 00:24:38,045
it's cheaper to iterate on paper,

467
00:24:38,085 --> 00:24:39,506
and I think this is a version of that.

468
00:24:40,406 --> 00:24:42,647
It's maybe also worth mentioning that all of this work

469
00:24:42,707 --> 00:24:44,648
I've described so far happened pretty quickly,

470
00:24:44,688 --> 00:24:45,868
about the first two months.

471
00:24:47,984 --> 00:24:49,406
One thing that helped us a great deal

472
00:24:50,166 --> 00:24:51,688
as we were doing all of this was

473
00:24:51,948 --> 00:24:55,171
a slightly exhaustive visual communication among the team.

474
00:24:55,211 --> 00:24:57,393
Little storyboards, if you will,

475
00:24:57,453 --> 00:24:59,775
that kind of describe tech needs

476
00:25:00,035 --> 00:25:01,917
or how a sequence of events should work.

477
00:25:02,858 --> 00:25:03,818
Since we didn't have

478
00:25:04,619 --> 00:25:08,462
a lot of time we couldn't afford to lose time due to miscommunication.

479
00:25:09,203 --> 00:25:16,349
So if we're ever kind of talking about a complex topic, we would do something up like this

480
00:25:16,749 --> 00:25:20,613
to make sure that all of these ideas were like completely thoroughly understood.

481
00:25:23,668 --> 00:25:28,891
I came to understand the value of this though through the context of my wider career.

482
00:25:29,031 --> 00:25:33,873
I've worked with a lot of different kinds of people in a lot of different spaces.

483
00:25:34,914 --> 00:25:41,417
Certainly teams like Pocket Watch, but also teams in academia, research teams, marketing

484
00:25:41,477 --> 00:25:45,780
teams, and I've learned that everybody communicates a little bit differently.

485
00:25:47,181 --> 00:25:53,844
So, working to convey a single idea in multiple different ways helps ensure that that idea

486
00:25:53,904 --> 00:25:58,026
is going to be understood regardless of what kind of communicator is on the other end.

487
00:25:58,787 --> 00:26:05,911
Taking a little bit of time to communicate clearly, in my experience, helps prevent miscommunication

488
00:26:05,971 --> 00:26:08,232
which can be super costly sometimes.

489
00:26:09,812 --> 00:26:13,999
But we eventually had to move from these nice looking mockups

490
00:26:14,080 --> 00:26:15,522
and start putting the stuff in the game

491
00:26:15,783 --> 00:26:17,766
and wrestle with the two or three weeks

492
00:26:17,867 --> 00:26:19,610
where the game looked like an awkward teenager,

493
00:26:20,291 --> 00:26:21,513
which is what this is right here.

494
00:26:23,928 --> 00:26:30,971
So at this point I proceeded to create at least one of every major asset type in the

495
00:26:31,011 --> 00:26:31,231
game.

496
00:26:31,271 --> 00:26:35,093
So at least one commander, at least one unit, at least one building.

497
00:26:36,053 --> 00:26:38,434
And the goal was twofold.

498
00:26:40,375 --> 00:26:41,996
one, to get like a first-hand,

