00:33:01,678 --> 00:33:04,280
I went with a pipeline that I knew worked.

610
00:33:04,781 --> 00:33:06,823
It was a little long and a little clumsy,

611
00:33:06,883 --> 00:33:07,763
but I knew it worked.

612
00:33:08,985 --> 00:33:11,847
What I would do is I'd do the rough animation in Flash.

613
00:33:11,907 --> 00:33:14,609
I'd export it out without anti-aliasing.

614
00:33:15,330 --> 00:33:17,112
I'd rebuild the sequence in Photoshop,

615
00:33:17,132 --> 00:33:18,453
and then I would just paint the frames.

616
00:33:20,385 --> 00:33:24,028
This was the same pipeline I developed to create a trailer of a little unreleased

617
00:33:25,408 --> 00:33:28,430
game that Chickadee was making in-house. It was clumsy for that

618
00:33:29,911 --> 00:33:32,733
because the characters were bigger, the sequences were longer,

619
00:33:33,853 --> 00:33:36,615
the shading was a little bit more complex and had to be tracked. Basically

620
00:33:36,635 --> 00:33:38,396
there's just like more of everything.

621
00:33:39,056 --> 00:33:41,017
If I got to Photoshop and I realized like

622
00:33:41,878 --> 00:33:47,021
I wanted a core change. I would kind of try and make it happen right there, but usually

623
00:33:47,061 --> 00:33:50,563
I'd have to go back to flash and that means any painting I had already done would be scrapped

624
00:33:50,823 --> 00:33:54,545
and it was this like really cumbersome back and forth thing that just took a lot of time.

