00:52:15,061 --> 00:52:18,526
And we did that because game development.

995
00:52:20,708 --> 00:52:21,229
So.

996
00:52:22,412 --> 00:52:27,834
Before I go any further, I should be like absolutely clear from this point on this is like personal reflection

997
00:52:28,975 --> 00:52:31,196
This isn't pocket watch. It's not even really chickadee

998
00:52:31,236 --> 00:52:34,837
It's just you know one guy who makes games kind of reflecting on that stuff

999
00:52:34,878 --> 00:52:40,220
It's a little bit like a like a personal post-mortem except the games not out yet, so it's like a pre post-mortem

1000
00:52:40,460 --> 00:52:41,301
I guess I don't know

1001
00:52:43,513 --> 00:52:47,335
So the extended development was seeded, I think,

1002
00:52:48,116 --> 00:52:50,758
by our improved standing with gamers and press.

1003
00:52:51,818 --> 00:52:54,740
When I started on the project,

1004
00:52:54,760 --> 00:52:57,222
I think there was a little bit of a fear among the team

1005
00:52:57,262 --> 00:53:00,404
that this was maybe a niche game and it might bomb.

1006
00:53:01,365 --> 00:53:03,646
The increased visibility and excitement

1007
00:53:03,907 --> 00:53:06,889
reduced those concerns, but replaced them

1008
00:53:06,969 --> 00:53:09,190
with the worry that maybe a minimum viable product

1009
00:53:09,270 --> 00:53:10,271
wasn't gonna be enough.

1010
00:53:13,024 --> 00:53:14,485
And then this guy joined the team,

1011
00:53:15,546 --> 00:53:17,107
and he began wagging his jaw.

1012
00:53:20,310 --> 00:53:22,071
Some of that wagging was pretty decent.

1013
00:53:22,512 --> 00:53:23,893
It made decent sense, right?

1014
00:53:25,914 --> 00:53:26,775
It felt logical.

1015
00:53:28,396 --> 00:53:31,519
Some of it was a little more superfluous.

1016
00:53:34,127 --> 00:53:39,252
If you've been in games, if you've made a game even as a student, you kind of know about

1017
00:53:39,752 --> 00:53:40,813
the feature creep.

1018
00:53:41,594 --> 00:53:46,758
A lot, maybe most of his ideas are cool, but he talks in box bullet points.

1019
00:53:47,299 --> 00:53:53,264
He doesn't really consider objective merit or time, but he appeals to emotion like a

1020
00:53:53,344 --> 00:53:56,507
great salesman, and it's really hard to not listen.

1021
00:53:58,068 --> 00:53:59,529
Let's take a look at the weather system.

1022
00:54:00,652 --> 00:54:05,435
As an example, the weather system allows us to do surprise different kinds of weather,

1023
00:54:05,455 --> 00:54:07,716
but also different times of day.

1024
00:54:07,736 --> 00:54:09,557
And it makes the screenshots look super zazzy.

1025
00:54:09,577 --> 00:54:10,718
They look really, really nice.

1026
00:54:12,407 --> 00:54:14,788
But it dismantles the visual hierarchy a bit.

1027
00:54:15,189 --> 00:54:17,950
It flattens values and homogenizes color.

1028
00:54:18,070 --> 00:54:19,851
It actually makes the game harder to play.

1029
00:54:20,931 --> 00:54:23,753
As a visual purist, I lament that loss of clarity,

1030
00:54:23,793 --> 00:54:27,695
but at the same time, it makes for a more marketable product

1031
00:54:27,775 --> 00:54:30,236
as far as screenshots and video are concerned.

1032
00:54:30,336 --> 00:54:31,337
It looks fancier.

1033
00:54:32,777 --> 00:54:33,698
So was it worth it?

1034
00:54:35,054 --> 00:54:35,534
I don't know.

1035
00:54:35,594 --> 00:54:37,776
I suppose it depends on what metric you're measuring.

1036
00:54:38,697 --> 00:54:41,459
But our process, I think, was undeniably messy.

1037
00:54:42,300 --> 00:54:45,142
We took an idea suggested by FeatureCreep.

1038
00:54:45,302 --> 00:54:47,905
We didn't do our homework beforehand

1039
00:54:47,945 --> 00:54:49,606
to figure out the true scope of it.

1040
00:54:50,647 --> 00:54:52,849
And we implemented it before we had a mock-up.

1041
00:54:52,889 --> 00:54:56,512
We basically tossed aside a bunch of the very practices

1042
00:54:56,812 --> 00:54:58,654
that led to our previous success.

1043
00:54:59,475 --> 00:55:08,243
This wasn't a brick laid in surface to a carefully considered long-term plan or even really a poorly considered long-term plan.

1044
00:55:08,304 --> 00:55:10,926
It was just a brick that we kind of like the shape of.

1045
00:55:11,467 --> 00:55:14,870
So who knows if we actually needed it to finish our house?

1046
00:55:16,772 --> 00:55:20,756
It may be made for a better product, but did it make for a better game?

1047
00:55:23,724 --> 00:55:25,606
I don't want to give the wrong impression either.

1048
00:55:25,886 --> 00:55:28,989
We were all working really hard during this time.

1049
00:55:29,049 --> 00:55:35,695
We were adding new features, we were showing the game off at conventions, we were considering

1050
00:55:35,775 --> 00:55:37,797
publishing and platform possibilities.

1051
00:55:38,258 --> 00:55:39,299
Seasons passed.

1052
00:55:41,196 --> 00:55:45,879
I think we're all just, you know, like trying to make the game better bit by bit, and that's

1053
00:55:45,959 --> 00:55:50,542
cool, that's a very organic way to approach game development, and I think there are times

1054
00:55:50,562 --> 00:55:53,624
when that's exactly how you want to approach your craft.

1055
00:55:54,584 --> 00:55:59,628
But in comparing the first year I was on Tooth and Tail to the second, I think all evidence

1056
00:55:59,708 --> 00:56:03,910
points to the fact that we did our best work when we were under a deadline.

1057
00:56:05,735 --> 00:56:09,137
uh... the initial you know get this done by the end of the year deadline was

1058
00:56:09,217 --> 00:56:10,337
self-imposed but

1059
00:56:10,857 --> 00:56:14,398
uh... we stuck to it and help focus our decision-making we didn't have time to

1060
00:56:14,418 --> 00:56:15,439
be wishy-washy

1061
00:56:15,859 --> 00:56:18,060
the week-long crunch for the course commercial

1062
00:56:18,080 --> 00:56:22,181
uh... forced me to quickly test a few ideas that turned out to be game

1063
00:56:22,221 --> 00:56:22,621
changers

1064
00:56:25,442 --> 00:56:25,602
now

1065
00:56:27,680 --> 00:56:31,984
Obviously, the reality of game development is that it's time consuming.

1066
00:56:33,305 --> 00:56:33,686
I get it.

1067
00:56:33,766 --> 00:56:39,471
And I'm not trying to argue that through the magic of project management, you can find

1068
00:56:39,531 --> 00:56:43,334
a secret shortcut from the kitchen to the study.

1069
00:56:44,295 --> 00:56:45,256
That was about Clue.

1070
00:56:45,276 --> 00:56:48,098
A little esoteric, I know, but I really wanted to put it in there.

1071
00:56:50,104 --> 00:56:53,488
But I will say that smart, consistent project management,

1072
00:56:53,608 --> 00:56:55,570
in this case, you know, slowing down to think

1073
00:56:55,610 --> 00:56:58,934
about our approach, having a clear goal in mind,

1074
00:56:59,554 --> 00:57:01,476
tossing dead time into a schedule

1075
00:57:01,516 --> 00:57:02,497
for when things don't work out,

1076
00:57:02,517 --> 00:57:04,460
basically all the stuff that I just spent 45 minutes

1077
00:57:04,520 --> 00:57:08,724
talking about, it allowed us to get about 12 months

1078
00:57:08,744 --> 00:57:10,126
of artwork done in about 10.

1079
00:57:10,206 --> 00:57:12,408
We were like art machines that first year.

1080
00:57:14,404 --> 00:57:16,725
In the second year, we were way less efficient.

1081
00:57:17,766 --> 00:57:18,746
We wasted time.

1082
00:57:18,946 --> 00:57:21,208
Now, I'm sure many of you can think

1083
00:57:21,248 --> 00:57:23,549
of inefficient development cycles

1084
00:57:23,849 --> 00:57:25,810
and think of how expensive it is,

1085
00:57:25,930 --> 00:57:27,651
like, oh, that's extra monthly burn.

1086
00:57:28,651 --> 00:57:30,092
And that's true, but I think that's a very

1087
00:57:30,812 --> 00:57:32,753
business-oriented way to view

1088
00:57:33,914 --> 00:57:35,275
the downside of poor planning.

1089
00:57:35,915 --> 00:57:39,056
I think the steeper cost is far more human.

1090
00:57:40,874 --> 00:57:45,897
The monetary costs of your development are recoupable, but your time is not.

1091
00:57:48,219 --> 00:57:49,640
So something to think about.

1092
00:57:50,901 --> 00:57:57,425
If through thoughtful planning and disciplined management, you were able to release a game

1093
00:57:57,565 --> 00:57:59,867
three months earlier than you would have otherwise.

1094
00:58:00,723 --> 00:58:02,044
That's effectively free time.

1095
00:58:02,664 --> 00:58:04,005
What would you do with that time?

1096
00:58:04,585 --> 00:58:06,866
Would you prototype a new game?

1097
00:58:06,886 --> 00:58:08,007
Would you dive back into it?

1098
00:58:08,427 --> 00:58:11,529
Would you learn a new skill or gain an experience

1099
00:58:11,589 --> 00:58:13,950
that would inform your future game making?

1100
00:58:15,259 --> 00:58:17,921
or maybe you would just go outside once in a while

1101
00:58:17,981 --> 00:58:19,402
and spend time with loved ones.

1102
00:58:21,044 --> 00:58:21,984
Again, I get it.

1103
00:58:22,465 --> 00:58:25,047
Development is just hard and it takes a lot of time,

1104
00:58:25,447 --> 00:58:28,850
but poor planning is just about the dumbest,

1105
00:58:30,131 --> 00:58:32,273
most pointless, most avoidable,

1106
00:58:32,393 --> 00:58:36,637
just shittiest excuse for wasting time.

1107
00:58:38,760 --> 00:58:40,641
you're not getting it back, none of us are.

1108
00:58:42,222 --> 00:58:44,784
The time we spend on our games comes from someplace,

1109
00:58:44,844 --> 00:58:47,746
it comes from every other experience we might gain

1110
00:58:47,866 --> 00:58:49,006
if we weren't doing that.

1111
00:58:50,968 --> 00:58:54,470
Simply put, to borrow a phrase from Andy Nguyen,

1112
00:58:54,670 --> 00:58:56,431
one of the other pocket watch folks,

1113
00:58:57,291 --> 00:58:58,913
he talks about maximizing value,

1114
00:58:58,953 --> 00:59:00,433
the man likes to find a good deal.

1115
00:59:02,735 --> 00:59:05,036
I think simply put, it's tragic to not maximize

1116
00:59:05,076 --> 00:59:06,117
the value of your life.

1117
00:59:08,557 --> 00:59:11,258
But I'll tell you what, this is heavy, right?

1118
00:59:11,318 --> 00:59:13,479
We thought we were learning about pipelines and stuff,

1119
00:59:13,519 --> 00:59:15,020
and it's like, what's this guy talking about now?

1120
00:59:16,120 --> 00:59:17,201
I don't wanna come off as a bummer,

1121
00:59:17,941 --> 00:59:19,162
or defeatist or anything like that,

1122
00:59:19,202 --> 00:59:21,323
because Tooth & Tail, actually, in my eyes,

1123
00:59:22,203 --> 00:59:23,924
is already an incredible success,

1124
00:59:24,424 --> 00:59:25,324
and we haven't launched yet.

1125
00:59:26,485 --> 00:59:28,826
But it's a success, not for any of the reasons

1126
00:59:29,666 --> 00:59:30,767
I've talked about in the last hour.

1127
00:59:31,127 --> 00:59:33,428
It's successful because it brought people,

1128
00:59:33,468 --> 00:59:35,889
it brought other human beings, it brought them together.

1129
00:59:38,101 --> 00:59:42,022
Even before launch, Tooth & Tail has had an astounding community.

1130
00:59:42,042 --> 00:59:47,283
And this is largely thanks to the cultivation efforts of Andy Nguyen,

1131
00:59:47,303 --> 00:59:48,964
the guy that I just mentioned.

1132
00:59:49,984 --> 00:59:52,285
This is a community that's hundreds and hundreds of people

1133
00:59:52,905 --> 00:59:54,385
before we ever launched. Active players.

1134
00:59:54,405 --> 00:59:55,965
And I don't say this like, oh, it's a stats thing.

1135
00:59:56,346 --> 00:59:59,706
It's, it's, this is, these are people all over the world

1136
01:00:00,407 --> 01:00:03,687
sharing their excitement and happiness and they're learning together.

1137
01:00:04,488 --> 01:00:06,808
Old players help new players learn the game.

1138
01:00:08,389 --> 01:00:11,853
They invent new strategies and record them and put them online.

1139
01:00:11,913 --> 01:00:13,554
It's like, oh my God, do you see what that guy did?

1140
01:00:14,015 --> 01:00:17,638
There are people who modded the game before it's ever been released.

1141
01:00:17,679 --> 01:00:23,945
There are people who are learning how to make games by modding our little unreleased game.

1142
01:00:24,125 --> 01:00:25,386
That is mind-blowing to me.

1143
01:00:27,168 --> 01:00:31,593
One community member, CapnFog, that's him right on the second third of the image right

